AGI -&nbsp;Hamas announced that its negotiating delegation left the Egyptian capital Cairo> to return to the capital of Qatar, Doha>. A spokesman added that Hamas accepted the document submitted by the mediators for a ceasefire > in Gaza. Al-Jazeera.&nbsp;Izzat al-Rishq, a member of the Hamas politburian, said that the Israeli invasion of the city of Rafah and the occupation of the relevant passage aim to block the efforts of the mediators to reach a truce. Al-Rishq confirmed that the negotiating delegation of the Islamist movement left Cairo for Doha, ensuring "the commitment to approving the mediator document on ceasefire in the Gaza Strip".
&nbsp;
<h2>Netanyahu: "Based pressures, Israel against Hamas also alone</h2>
"Today we face again enemies willing to destroy us," "I tell the leaders of the world: no pressure, no decision by any international forum will prevent Israel from defending itself." "If Israel is forced to remain alone, Israel will remain alone." The Israeli Prime Minister Benjanim Netanyahu says this on the occasion of the Holocaust Memorial Day in Jerusalem, in what seems to be an answer to the decision of US President Joe Biden to suspend arms shipments to Israel. "Innumerable people all over the world support our right cause," said Netanyahu, "we will defeat our Genocide enemies."
<h2>Biden confirms, stop selling weapons to Israel if it invades Rafah</h2>
The President of the United States Joe Biden> has confirmed that he will interrupt some deliveries of offensive weapons to Israel > in the event of an offensive against Rafah. How to proceed on the ground in Gaza and Lebanon, in the light of the White House's decision to block some shipments of weapons, will be decided tonight during the "fatidics" meetings of the war cabinet and the security cabinet of Israel. The newspaper Israel Hayom, citing an anonymous Israeli official, says that in the last Sunday call between Biden and the premier, Benjamin Netanyahu, the latter assured that the Jewish state "will deal with nails and teeth if necessary". "And he was serious," the official said.
&nbsp;
<h2>Oms, hospitals in southern Gaza have fuel for three days
The southern hospitals of the Gaza Strip have only three days of fuel > said the head of the World Health Organization (Oms), > because of the closure of border crossings in Rafah>. Despite international objections, yesterday Israel sent the tanks to the overcrowded southern city of Rafah and closed the nearby crossing with Egypt, which is the main access channel for aid to the Palestinian territory besieged. "The closure of the border crossing continues to prevent the United Nations from carrying fuel. Without fuel, all humanitarian operations will stop. The closure of the border also prevents the delivery of humanitarian aid to Gaza," says General Manager, Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus on X. "The hospitals in southern Gaza have only three days of fuel, which means that the services could soon stop." &nbsp;
&nbsp;
<h2>Hamas: new common pit in Al-Shifa, exhumed 49 bodies</h2>
The Hamas> government in the Gaza Strip has identified a new common pit > from which 49 bodies have already been exhumed in the Al Shifa hospital. The authorities of Gaza state that rescue teams continue to dissuade the bodies and expect to find "new bodies" in the common pit, the third found in the hospital center from which about 400 deaths have already been recovered, according to a statement. During operations at the hospital, Israel claimed to have killed some 200 alleged militants and questioned more than 800 suspects, including identifying about 500 members of Hamas and Palestinian Islamic Jihad, including senior officials. So far, according to Hamas, seven common pits were found in the Gaza Strip hospitals, three of which in Naser, three Khan Yunis (south) and another in the Kamal Adwan hospital (north).
